        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New Orleans</placeName>
                <date>August 21st/65</date>-</p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p>Revd. &amp; Dear Sir!</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Father being absent from home on a<lb/> tour of recreation, I take
                the liberty to answer yours<lb/> of the <date>8th</date> inst. which as you see came
                duly to hand.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">In answer to your question, why you did not<lb/> hear from father
                the particulars about his leaving the Cong.<lb/> here, I can only Say, that Father
                dislikes to boast of his<lb/> good deeds and what he accomplished in the Cong.
                During<lb/> his administration of four years, and this to my knowledge<lb/> was the
                main reason for father's not doing so. But a<lb/> young friend of Father here had
                prepared a report which<lb/> was intended for your valuable journal, and which
                was<lb/> withheld when the article concerning Father's leaving<lb/> the Cong.
                appeared in your journal, the young man<lb/> expecting to see some farther &amp;
                more minute report from<lb/> your Same correspondent, but nothing having
                appeared<lb/> he requested me to send you the above mentioned re=<lb/>port, and
                kindly request you to grant it a space in the<lb/> columns of your valuable journal.
                I therefore enclose<lb/> the report and make for my friend the above men=<lb/>tioned
                request. As to the bulk of its contents you<lb/> may, Revd. Sir rest fully assured,
                the young man is a gentleman<lb/> in the full sense of the word and stands high in
                the<lb/> regards of the citizens here, both jews &amp; gentiles.</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>Hoping that you will regard it as if it had come<lb/> from Father and grant it a
                space in the columns<lb/> of your valuable periodical</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I remain Revd. Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">with the highest regard</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">your most obedient Servt.</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <persName role="author">Henry Illoway</persName>
            </p>
            <p>PS./ <persName>Mr Wechsler</persName> was here as a candidate and<lb/> preached it
                seems to me, on Shalion<add>?</add>
                <add>עם הארץ ברסיקא</add> and on<lb/>
                <date>Sunday</date>; on <date>Saturday</date> he preached in english which<lb/> was
                mistaken for german, and on <date>Sunday</date> he preached<lb/> in german which
                sounded like russian, he is an<lb/>
                <add>Hebrew</add> but still styles himself Revd. Dr. having<lb/>
                <sic>recieved</sic> his “Tibloma” from <persName>Dr Wise</persName> as a reward<lb/>
                for his faithful services in promoting the exterpation<add>?</add><lb/> of pigs from
                this continent by “Devouring their meat”<lb/> In his sermon on <date>Saturday</date>
                not having been fully<lb/> acquainted yet with the principles of a majority of
                the<lb/> present Cong. he said “I can go backward and I can<lb/> go forward” That's
                constancy; very good for reformers.</p>
